    </div>
    <p class="cap">Every "Verdict" call above is ours, from raising and DNA-sexing both — not aggregated from other websites.</p>
    <h3 class="cag-h3">What Does the Male vs Female Comparison Table Show?</h3>
    <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/male-vs-female-african-grey-side-by-side-comparison-chart.webp" srcset="/male-vs-female-african-grey-side-by-side-comparison-chart-760.webp 760w, /male-vs-female-african-grey-side-by-side-comparison-chart.webp 1376w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1376" height="768" alt="Field-guide comparison chart of a male versus female African Grey showing identical appearance, size, talking and temperament, with DNA as the only way to sex them" loading="lazy">
    <p>Read down the verdict column and the story tells itself: appearance, size, talking, temperament and bonding all land on "the individual bird, not the sex." The two rows that actually break by sex are biological — a hen can lay eggs and carries the calcium consideration that comes with it, and hormonal seasons show up a little differently in each. For the question most buyers arrive with — which is better, male or female — the table's answer is that you're choosing between two versions of the same excellent companion.</p>
