  <!-- S16 MYTHS -->
  <section id="myths">
    <h2 class="cag-h2">Male vs Female African Grey Myths — What's Actually True?</h2>
    <p>The sex myths arrive in our inbox pre-installed — buyers quote them to us before we've said a word. Mainstream references such as <a href="https://www.thesprucepets.com/facts-about-african-grey-parrots-390715" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">The Spruce Pets' African Grey overview ↗</a> already note the species is monomorphic and behaviorally individual; below is where each piece of folklore parts ways with what our own clutches do.</p>
    <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/male-vs-female-african-grey-myths-vs-reality-cards.webp" srcset="/male-vs-female-african-grey-myths-vs-reality-cards-760.webp 760w, /male-vs-female-african-grey-myths-vs-reality-cards.webp 1408w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 768px" width="1408" height="768" alt="Myth versus reality cards debunking claims that female African Greys are always calmer, that Greys prefer one owner gender, and that males talk better" loading="lazy">
    <h3 class="cag-h3">Which Sex Myths Land in Our Inbox Every Week?</h3>
    <p>Two short debunks, then the heavyweight claim goes under the microscope.</p>
    <div class="myth-grid">
      <div class="myth-c"><span class="myth-x">Myth</span><p><strong>"Hens are always calmer."</strong> We've raised placid cocks and spirited hens and the reverse. Calm is an individual temperament with the same range in both sexes — routine, enrichment and handling shape it far more than chromosomes do.</p></div>
      <div class="myth-c"><span class="myth-x">Myth</span><p><strong>"Greys prefer a man / a woman."</strong> A hand-reared grey bonds to whoever shows up consistently and reads its body language — not to the owner's gender. Men and women both raise deeply bonded birds here, with cocks and hens alike.</p></div>
    </div>
    <h4 class="cag-h4">So Do Males Really Talk Better? The Claim, Under the Microscope</h4>
    <p>The most repeated claim online, usually stated as law.</p>
    <img class="sec-img inf-img" src="/myth-male-african-greys-talk-better-debunk-infographic.webp" srcset="/myth-male-african-greys-talk-better-debunk-infographic-760.webp 760w, /myth-male-african-greys-talk-better-debunk-infographic.webp 1408w" sizes="(max-width:900px) 92vw, 760px" width="1408" height="768" alt="Infographic debunking the myth that male African Greys talk better than females, showing both sexes reach the same vocabulary with equal handling" loading="lazy">
    <h5 class="cag-h5">The Reality: The Individual Bird Talks, Not the Sex</h5>
    <p>Owners report brilliant hens and quiet cocks just as often as the reverse; how much you talk to the bird and how hand-tame it is drive vocabulary far more than sex does. Our honest version: there is no reliable talking gap between cocks and hens — pick the chatty individual in front of you, not a chromosome.</p>
    <h6 class="cag-h6">Citation: owner reports across both sexes</h6>
    <p>Sample the big grey-owner communities on Reddit or Facebook and the reports line up with our nursery ledger: brilliant hens, quiet cocks, and no sex-linked talking edge that survives a real clutch.</p>
  </section>

